Purpose
The Dual Factory System is the first industrial capability installed on the RAMA Hub. Its job is to take raw lunar regolith boxes arriving from the Moon and convert them into structural components for expanding the hub and building new orbital systems.

Two factories operate as a mirrored pair for redundancy, throughput, and safety.

Factory Layout
Each factory consists of:

One feeder line (accepts incoming regolith boxes)

One processing oven (melts regolith into usable material)

One forming line (extrudes beams, plates, brackets, or cable anchors)

One cooling rack

One storage rack for finished parts

The two factories are mounted on opposite sides of the hub for balance.

Why Two Factories?
1. Redundancy
If one fails, the other keeps RAMA alive.

2. Continuous Operation
While one is cooling or resetting, the other can run hot.

3. Load Balancing
Incoming regolith boxes can be routed to whichever factory is ready.

4. Safety
If a thermal event occurs, the mirrored layout prevents hub‑wide damage.

Material Flow
Incoming regolith box arrives in orbit

Box is captured and routed to a factory

Box is opened and emptied into the feeder

Regolith enters the oven

Material is melted and homogenized

Molten material is extruded into:

L‑brackets

Cable anchors

Beam segments

Plates

Parts cool on racks

Finished components are stored for MOE assembly

Power Source
Solar arrays feed both factories

Mirror arrays can concentrate heat into the ovens

Factories can run in sunlight or shadow

Design Philosophy
Identical twins: both factories are the same model

Modular: each subsystem can be replaced independently

Simple: no exotic alloys, no precision metallurgy

Robust: built to run for years with minimal intervention

Expandable: more factories can be added as RAMA grows

Why This Matters
The Dual Factory System:

Turns lunar dirt into orbital structure

Enables RAMA to grow without Earth launches

Creates the first true off‑world industrial loop

Allows the hub to expand from 20 rim sections to 40, 60, 100+

Makes RAMA a self‑building system

This is where RAMA stops being a structure and becomes an ecosystem.
